The black box in your car?
As American road designers struggle to find money to repair a crumbling highway network, many are beginning to see the solution in a little black box that easily fits into the dashboard of your car.
Devices that track every mile driven by a motorist and that transmit this information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial effort by Washington and the state planning agencies to revamp the outdated system of financing America's highways.
The usual fashionable design of motorways suddenly sparked intense debate and the formation of various associations.
Libertarians met with environmental groups and lobbied for the government to use these little boxes that would record the kilometers you've driven and maybe even where you're going, and then use that information to compile the tax returns.
The Tea Party is terrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has mentioned a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress can't agree to continue, some states are waiting for nothing.
They're looking at how they can move over the next decade to a system where the driver pays for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken the black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real national emergency.
"It's not a matter of having a lot of choice", said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of State Governments, which plans to start tracking the mileage of every Californian motorist in the state by 2025.
It's going to change the way we pay those taxes.
That's what this technology is for.
The point is that the Road Trust Fund, funded by the taxes Americans pay at gas stations, is bankrupt.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars will go a lot more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't been raised in 20 years.
With the current high price of gasoline, politicians are reluctant to raise the tax by even a single penny.
'A gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,' said Lee Munnich, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His government recently installed tracking devices in 500 cars to test this mileage-paying system.
In the long term, this seems to be the most logical alternative, he said.
Experts call it a mileage charge.
Not surprisingly, this idea appeals to urban liberals, since taxes can be used to change drivers' behavior patterns, which can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California designers look to this system to plan strategies to meet the goals set out in ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free-market leaders from the Reason Foundation are also in favor of the idea of drivers paying for miles.
"It's not a tax that disappears into a black hole", said Adrian Moore, vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay for what they get.
The initiative is also supported by two former US transportation secretaries who in 2011 urged Congress to move towards pay-per-mile.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
The House of Representatives, however, rejected the proposal, due to the concerns of rural legislators representing the population, whose daily life often involves travelling many kilometres to work outside the city.
Still, a number of states and cities are making progress on their own.
The most hotly contested is Oregon, which has 5,000 drivers in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the state a mileage tax instead of a gas tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York is currently reviewing the project.
Illinois is trying to do this to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 state transportation departments, along with the eastern seaboard states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) are studying how they can implement this change.
But there are not all who support this concept.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently fitted with the device, drivers were concerned about the government's ability to track their every move.
