The pursuit of such technology has led some government agencies to a small company in California called True Mileage.
This company was not originally involved in the scheme to assist the government in taxing drivers.
She wanted to break into the emerging market of legal liability insurance, where drivers would pay based on how much they drove.
But this device he's testing is attracting the attention of road network designers because it doesn't use GPS and delivers only a limited amount of information that is regularly recorded by a modem.
"People will be more willing to go if you're not tracking their speed and their location", says Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
