George Kerevan: A divided Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another scary story about independence.
This time, the warning appears that the condition for an independent Scotland to join the EU would be its entry into Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport controls in Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
The truth is that the Strathclyde papers mentioned the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but as you might expect, that didn't make the headlines.
Nor did anyone mention that EU Member States spend a lot of time adapting their official laws if that is convenient for them.
Since Scotland is now out of Schengen, the offer of continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession to Brussels in return for whatever it really wants from the Scots.
So it's a pretty weak story.
I heard a journalist duck say that "independence means passport control" at least 40 years ago.
Yet, there is an interesting thought behind this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to listen to Europe?
Why would you trade a London chump for a Brussels one, especially now?
This is the real story of Europe: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
As a result of the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties dedicated to opposing the EU or abolishing the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party founded this year came out of nowhere and already won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, effectively replacing the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) in the Bundestag.
There has always been opposition at home to the idea of a federal Europe.
But the current economic crisis has become a defining moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, along with the straitjacket placed on national economies through the clinging to the common currency, have led many to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running large budget deficits - this was true only of Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that locks its members into exchange rates that are favourable to German exporters  and that German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing its domestic currency, southern Europe is at a disadvantage vis-à-vis Germany in terms of domestic production.
The only help is to cut public revenue and expenditure, which Germany is urging.
Beyond the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper cause of European malfunctioning.
As a result of the 'green' energy policy promoted by Brussels  code to support French and German companies at the expense of consumers , European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for petrol as it does in the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have seen in the case of Grangemouth.
All the wage freezes in the world wouldn't stop the European petrochemical industry from being flooded with cheap US shale oil.
The result is a growing rebellion, especially in France, once an ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany in check and allow Paris to rise to Washington's level in the world.
But Berlin no longer needed Paris as a proof of political legitimacy and imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, pro-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists into third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote  a timely warning to British Labour that they cannot assume that a split on the right will automatically turn left.
How does Le Pen handle her newfound popularity among the white working class?
It would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc across the European Parliament, working against the common currency.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in history.
I think that in the near future, the growing anti-European sentiment and the anti-common currency sentiment will merge and destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather become something more free in the sense of 'a Europe of (sovereign) nations' favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and to join the US.
However, Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
And where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be a region of (in principle) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - including the ability to tell Berlin and Brussels when to leave us alone.
I suppose Scotland would do well in the loose order of Europe provided it kept its own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should follow the example of Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is  oddly  the most successful non-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a large majority in 2011 thanks to the opposition to the cuts planned (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the subsequent Conservative-Liberal Democrat coalition.
It would be ridiculous if Scotland now voted for independence just to accept austerity measures dictated by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Maturing earlier
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
Physical changes do not indicate that you are approaching puberty
No evidence of hormones or other chemicals
Experts say that the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty.
The trend of earlier puberty is not as apparent in boys.
Former CNN reporter Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be alarmed when her daughter starts to grow breasts and pubic hair at the age of 7 or 8?
At the annual meeting of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are fairly common among American girls and represent a new standard.
"I spent a lot of time reassuring my parents that it's not usually a sign of rapid development toward full puberty", Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, hair growth on the thighs and armpits, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Over the past 40 years, however, there has been little change in the age at which a woman begins menstruating.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, compared with 12.75 years in 1970.
"When breasts start to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the first menstrual period occurs", said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem".
The most reliable test of how puberty will progress is time.
There is debate about what activates the actual onset of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before age 8, a girl is considered to be "premature".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops  and can be monitored closely by paediatricians.
The faster growth may be the reason for the endocrinologist to perform tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumour or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent the further effects of premature bone ageing, which can eventually lead to stunted growth and girth in adulthood.
Recommendations for medication and hormone therapy depend on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about the use of medication, but acknowledges that "suppressing puberty can alleviate a girl's behavioral problems and her feelings of being different from her peers".
Understandably, the other big problem is that parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have their period.
"They're worried about her getting pregnant or how she's going to handle the hygiene", Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock", recalls one woman whose daughter began menstruating at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of precocious puberty.
However, there is no coherent body of evidence yet that the hormones in milk or other foods, the chemicals in the environment, or the sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz is pushing the assumption that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study in girls aged 6 to 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are various explanations.
From a global perspective, it seems that patterns of early puberty are influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another puzzle: Although facial and pubic hair appear in boys at an early age, the trend toward full-blown puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of Pediatricians (AAP) conference added to the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty", said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goryeo Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek guidance from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
'It may mean having to talk to your child sooner than you expect,' advised Kaplowitz.
If you remain calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that, although this is premature, it is a normal part of life.
