As the eating habits change, people are bigger, but the seats on the airplanes haven't changed radically.
From the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 jumbo defined modern long-haul air travel, to the turn of the century, the average weight of the American between the ages of 40 and 49, according to the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, increased by 10 percent.
According to the U.S. National Center for Health Statistics, the average American in the 21st century is three feet tall.
Airbus claims that its rival is sticking to the seat concept from the 1950s, when the average width of the newly christened aircraft's seats was lower.
Airbus claims to have conducted research that suggests that a seat extension of one inch improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing rejects Airbus' seat dimensions, saying it is not the aircraft manufacturers' responsibility to decide how airlines export fees and equipment.
The company also says that research shows that the cabin experience depends on more than just the width of the seat.
"It's really about giving airlines flexibility and allowing them to do the things they believe they have to do to be successful", said Kent Craver, a cabin space expert.
They don't want us to dictate what makes them profit.
They know their business better than anyone.
For passengers, more elbow room is crucial, but for suppliers, it is a growing problem that can affect revenues.
Behind this spur is a race in aircraft orders, with estimated trade over the next decade worth at least $700 billion in catalogue prices, enough to tip the balance of American and European exports.
As Reuters reported in July, the seating layout is exactly what's fueling the battle between the last planes.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim that their latest twin-engine long-haul aircraft designs are 20 percent more efficient than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing's performance claims depend in part on comparing the design of the 777X with 10 seats in a row and the 777 concept with 9 seats in a row.
The unit cost benefit is weakened compared to the 10-seat concept.
