A new nicotine vaccine may take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that may take the pleasure out of smoking cigarettes.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
There's more testing to be done before human trials, which will take years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York says the early signs are good.
"We certainly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is so strong that it overcomes all current approaches", Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry the genetic information to create antinequin antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies hunt down any nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, thus preventing the smoker from getting nicotine shot.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice that were additionally given nicotine continued with their normal activities.
But the mice that weren't vaccinated were "calmed down", the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had entered their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given so frequently to maintain adequate levels of antibodies that they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of the new vaccine should be much lower, because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines were completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they would be tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
Smokers, however, are much more likely to use it to quit.
"They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get any benefit from it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them to get rid of this bad habit", he said.
The British scientists said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research is needed.
