Rules on the use of electronic devices on aircraft remain in force in Australia for the time being
Passengers on Australian airlines will continue to be required to switch off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite changes in the US to relax regulations on these devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) has given US airlines the space to change their practices so that passengers will be able to read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during critical phases of a flight, as long as the devices remain in flight mode.
Passengers can already do this for the majority of the flight, but many people are annoyed that they cannot access their electronic books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are reviewing this decision, which requires a great deal of work from US carriers to meet the requirements, but have indicated that they have no plans to change their practices anytime soon.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority (CASA) also said that it had examined the notification but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical phases of flight are still in place in Australia.
CASA currently has no specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft,he said.
This issue is covered by regulations that require aircraft operators to ensure that safety is maintained at all times and that passengers act in accordance with safety instructions received from crew members.
Virgin, which had already spoken to CASA about expanding the use of its in-flight wi-fi system, was in favour of the change but said it would be subject to the regulator's decision.
"We would like CASA to do an analysis of the permissibility of using electronic devices because we really think that now that we have [wireless onboard entertainment], it would improve the customer experience", the spokesman said.
Qantas has announced that it will stick to the current regulations for the time being.
"Our current policy is that electronic devices are not allowed to be used during take-off and landing, and we have no plans to change that anytime soon", he said.
The FAA rules apply to American airlines.
But we are constantly interested in regulatory developments that may be of interest to our passengers, and we certainly study the FAA's decision and the reasons behind it carefully.
For US air carriers, the impact of the rules will vary from company to company and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate mobile phone interference, and revise manuals, training material, hand baggage programs and passenger information.
Once an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable and lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-readers and smartphones at any altitude, the FAA said.
In the rare cases of low visibility, the crew shall instruct the passengers to switch off the equipment during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier equipment be stored safely under the seats or in an overhead storage area during takeoff and landing.
With the poverty of the middle class increasing, Singapore's pawn shops are booming
At a pawnshop in Singapore's Bendemeer Shopping Center, Janani Amirthalinga is pawning a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for her daughter's school fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house and I put all my money into it", says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she receives $2,400 a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family's monthly income is insufficient, she says.
Indeed, demand across Southeast Asia, where household debt is rising, is such that ValueMax, where the woman is conducting her transaction, became the third-highest-ranked pawnshop on the Singapore Exchange this week.
Jewelry freezing is not only a quick way to borrow SGD 1300 cash in Ms. Amirthalinga's case, but it is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Singaporean banks routinely apply an annual percentage rate of 17%, just above the 15.4% rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, the advantage of the halting stations is that they do not require a personal identification (payment history) or proof of income and can provide a loan more quickly than banks.
And so, with families feeling the strain of rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to pawn shops.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit supported by loose monetary policies in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to mortgage companies to deal with their worsening financial situation.
This week, the Standard & Poor's credit rating agency cited the rising use of credit by households, mainly due to rising rents, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in terms of gross domestic product.
Malaysia tops the list with a ratio of 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists were also concerned about Thailand's high level of consumer debt, which had barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed continued weak exports and weaker consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising costs, people from the middle to the low [income scale] will try to supplement their income wherever they can", said Song Seng Wun, an economist at Malaysia's CIMB Bank.
The historically high gold prices of the past two years have contributed to people's eagerly pledging their personal possessions and taking the opportunity to exchange their family jewelry for cash.
About 70 percent of the items pledged in the city's 200 pawn shops are gold.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, we'll stop Grandma's gold necklace and get it back next month".
The largest pledge operator in Thailand, EasyMoney, has seen a 20% increase in the number of customers using its pledge platform in recent months.
The growth in the pawnbroking industry is so strong that ValueMax, which operates a branch in the Bendemeer hub and 15 similar branches in Singapore, is planning to expand not only into neighbouring Malaysia  where it has four branches  but also outside of Asia, says ValueMax CEO Yeah Lee Ching.
The company will finance it using 60 percent of the 66 million SGD it raised this week on the Singapore Exchange.
While some discount lenders have come under fire for their high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says that the collateral not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but it also doesn't directly increase the debt.
Customers mortgage items they already own, and monetisation of personal property does not increase household debt,he says.
In society, asset pledging is increasingly accepted as a means of securing short-term, secure financing.
Moreover, those who use pawn shops are not just those in financial distress.
Wealthy Singaporeans also use ValueMax branches to pawn gold bars or Rolex watches, and they can get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers come from all walks of life.
'They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow for short-term purposes for their venture-based business or investment, or small businesses that need help solving cash flow problems,' says Ms Yeah.
Sometimes they just need the money as soon as possible.
