Syria has destroyed its chemical weapons production facilities, says watchdog
Syria has destroyed critical chemical weapons and poison gas munitions production equipment, the Global Chemical Weapons Monitoring Committee said Thursday, as violent conflict erupted in the country's north, not far from one of the sites where the toxic materials are believed to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said that since the start of the civil war nearly three years ago, more than 120,000 residents have been killed.
The notice from the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons came the day before November 1st,
the term designated by the Hague-based organization for Damascus for the destruction or disabling of all chemical weapons production facilities and chemical mixing equipment for the production of poison gas and munitions.
The completion of this essentially initial phase of destruction is a significant milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all of Damascus' chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the equipment means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and supplies.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons, including yperite and the nerve agent sarin.
The announcement came as fighting raged Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons factory and warehouse, the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
An activist group that has been monitoring the death toll in Syria through its network of activists reported Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are civilians, including 6,365 children.
The government side is said to have 29,954 members of Bashar al-Assad's armed forces, 18,678 pro-government fighters and 187 armed Lebanese Hezbollah fighters.
The death toll also includes 2,202 government defectors and some 5,375 opposition fighters, many of whom are foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated that 100,000 people had died in the conflict since March 2011.
That number hasn't been updated since.
The conflict has forced some 2 million people to leave the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting rebels in Safir, many of them linked to al-Qaeda, for weeks.
The Observatory said Thursday that there were casualties on both sides, but it didn't have a specific number.
The battles underscored the dangers faced by chemical weapons inspectors who are facing tight deadlines in their mission to rid Syria of its chemical arsenal amid the ongoing civil war.
In a statement, the OPCW, which works closely with the UN, said that its team is now 'satisfied' to have verified 'and monitored' the destruction of 'Syrian declared essential manufacturing and mixing/refuelling equipment'.
He added that 'no further inspection activities are currently planned'.
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
The inspectors said they were unable to visit two locations because of security concerns.
On Thursday, the OPCW said the two sites had been "abandoned" by Syria and... the chemical weapons program items it contained had been moved to two other declared sites that had been "checked".
It was not immediately clear whether the Safir facility was one of the places that OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has agreed to a plan to completely destroy its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPCW Executive Committee next month.
'I salute the courage and bravery you have shown in fulfilling the most demanding mission this organization has ever had,' said the Observatory's Director Ahmet Uzumcu in his comments issued by the OPCW.
Now in its third year, the civil war pits the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels against the Assad government and its security forces, which are full of Alawites, a branch of Shi'ite Islam.
As for the further development, the head of the Observatory, Rami Abdul Rahman, said that on Wednesday there was a strong explosion inside an air defence facility in the Syrian coastal province of Laziqiya.
He said the cause of the explosion was unknown.
