FAA: Airline passengers can now use technology on board (but not call from their mobile phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices gate-to-gate in addition to calling from their mobile phones  to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music, under highly anticipated new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
How quickly the change is implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft are compliant with the new rules and that they have updated their cabin crew training manuals and equipment stowage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly", the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors close.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches two miles and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again as the plane descends to land and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and boarding, the FAA said.
The Commission therefore considers that the aid measures in question constitute State aid within the meaning of Article 107 (1) of the Treaty.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Stewards, welcomed the change.
"Once the new rules are safely in place, and we will work closely with the transport companies to do so, it will be a success", Glading said in a statement.
We're getting tired of looking like scouts, to be honest.
However, surfing the Internet, sending e-mails and text messages, or downloading data will continue to be prohibited below 3 kilometers above sea level, the agency said.
Passengers will be advised to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
So still no Words with Friends, the online scrabble game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was famously thrown off an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will have to be stored further away for fear of being able to injure someone if they are flown around the cabin.
Cell phone calls will continue to be prohibited on board.
The rules for using cell phones are not set by the FAA, but by the U.S. Federal Communications Commission.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert for CBS News, said that cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are a real problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigational devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause airborne interference to broadcast towers", Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the problem last month recommended that the government allow for wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been under pressure in recent years to relax restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Senator Claire McCaskill, a Democrat from Missouri, argue that there is no legitimate security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of such devices is pervasive.
Some studies suggest that as many as a third of travelers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to the disruption of navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical achievement of the time.
The new airlines are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generation aircraft, but they are also designed, and certified by the FAA, to be resistant to electronic interference.
The Commission has also noted that the airport services agreement with Ryanair and the agreement with Ryanair were signed on the same day.
Plans modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to the increased use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
Modern electronic devices generally emit much less intense radio signals than did devices of previous generations.
For example, electronic readers emit only minimal transmissions when the page is turned.
But the transmission is stronger when the device downloads or sends data.
Among those pushing to loosen restrictions on travelers' use of these devices is Amazon.com.
In 2011, the company's representatives loaded a commercial airliner with their Kindle e-readers and conducted a test flight, but no problems were encountered.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether these facilities pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believes that the interference from these devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee stated that there are only fragmentary reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference to air traffic control systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off their devices during instrument flight in low visibility.
The travel industry group welcomed the changes and said it was a sensible move for the traveling public, who are a big user of the technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not at odds with safety", said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
