Is the European elite ready to trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing businesses together and defining what changes UK businesses and job-creating companies want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of leading British business people to ask their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov surveyed 1,000 business leaders representing UK businesses of all sizes and from all sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now looking to export outside Europe, and focusing on countries that are modernizing and growing, while EU countries are stagnating.
They want to see the government prefer new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil to the long and arduous process of reforming Europe's secretive institutions.
When we asked them for their views on specific policy areas - from monopoly regulation to product law - most business people felt that control of these key competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market and businessmen said that the costs of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of the European trading area.
And finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most telling finding, that a clear majority want Britain to pursue a treaty change and a relationship with the EU that should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings, which were shared by businesses of all sizes and major business groups, show that the business sector is pushing for 'meaningful change' that carries the impact back to Britain.
There is a lot at stake in getting a treaty change and a better deal for the UK could mean a gain of up to 16% in the referendum vote to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British business supports his plan to revise the terms of UK membership in the EU.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to represent a significant shift from the current balance of power back to Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible and, as the eurozone embarks on the path to closer economic and fiscal union, increasingly necessary.
The priority must be jobs and growth in Britain, and as our survey results show, for business this means a refocus on trade and a fundamental change in the regulatory approach to Brussels.
