Scientists have shed more light on how tail movements are related to a dog's mood
Previous research has shown that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from a dog's perspective), while nervous dogs wag their tails predominantly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different connections to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions".
We've tried to find the same thing in other species.
He added that, as in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs react to the disproportionate tail wagging of other dogs, researchers monitored animals that watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It may not be long before we understand why their tails sometimes turn one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: 'We showed the dogs films about dogs, either in a natural version or in silhouette, to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to modify the tail movement to make it look more to the right or to the left.'
When the animals saw the otherwise inconspicuous dog wagging its tail to the right (from the viewpoint of a dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly still.
But when she noticed that the tail was turned to the left (again from the viewpoint of a dog that was spinning its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals became uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he didn't think that dogs could consciously communicate with each other through these gestures.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they must and may not pay attention to.
He said, "If you encounter dogs repeatedly and the movement of their tails in one direction is repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior and the movement of the tails in the other direction produces less friendly behavior, you will respond based on that experience".
The researchers say the findings may help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand their animals' emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a senior lecturer in veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they see an aggressive dog, and to the right when they see a happy dog.
And in another study from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, "Dogs were more likely to date a dog robot when it was wagging its tail to the left than to the right, when they were more likely to become uncertain, and exactly the opposite of the Italian study".
The difference, he says, may be that dogs in these different animal studies in movies or dog robots didn't behave quite like dogs.
He explained that studies of how dogs react to real dogs might help.
Although there is strong evidence that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes in many different mammals, many details still need to be clarified  and dogs are no exception, he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won't take long to understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
