In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said that the formal promotion of the new cardinals will be preceded by a gathering of the current cardinals known as the consistory.
"Pope Francis has decided to communicate his decision to convene the February consistory in advance to facilitate the planning of other gatherings that require the participation of cardinals from different parts of the world", Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal voters is likely to fall by February.
He said that the pope usually appoints as many cardinals as are needed to bring the number of electors back up to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 years of age as he wants.
The consistory next year will be significant because it will be the first since Francis was elected in March of this year, Valero said.
At the moment, there is a certain orientation towards Europe, Europe and especially Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope nominates cardinals from the rest of the world to restore the balance", he said.
Forty percent of Roman Catholics are in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
It will also be the first election of cardinals since Francis established the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world whose task it is to find ways to reform the church.
