RBS suspends two foreign currency dealers
According to two people familiar with the situation, the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is suspending two dealers in its foreign exchange division, another sign that global investigations by regulators into suspected currency manipulation are becoming more frequent.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed they are cooperating with the competent authorities in their investigation of the world's largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion changes hands every day.
The two traders mentioned would be the first RBS employees to be suspended as part of the expanding investigation, which is a response to the LIBOR (London Interbank Offered Rate) manipulation scandal.
The bank declined to comment on the suspension, but confirmed it had received a request for information from the authorities this month.
"Our relentless investigation into this matter continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other authorities", the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the matter said that RBS had provided the UK Financial Conduct Authority with records of emails and instant messages sent from and to the accounts of the former trader.
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and is believed to have been relieved from his current position as European head of foreign exchange trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, the European head of cash trading at Citi, took a leave of absence this week, while Matt Gardiner, former head of currency trading at Barclays and UBS, was suspended this week by Standard Chartered.
None of these traders have been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr. Usher's instant messaging group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, people familiar with the matter said.
UBS said this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after the Swiss supervisory authority Finma announced it was investigating suspected foreign exchange market machinations at several Swiss banks.
At least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission, Finma, Swiss antitrust authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are investigating allegations that these bankers have colluded to manipulate the currency market.
In addition, people familiar with the situation said that HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse had launched internal investigations or received requests for information from the competent authorities.
Banks have been combing through years of old instant messages and emails to find instances of wrongdoing.
Reports of the investigations have alarmed traders in an area that has been one of the biggest engines for profit-making in investment banks' closing hours in recent years, but which has been disrupted by the fact that little currency volatility has limited opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to play down the gravity of the situation by claiming that a large and highly liquid foreign exchange market is essentially impossible to manipulate, but high-level traders say that may not necessarily be true.
A senior trader said that despite the significant volume of daily foreign exchange trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and banks, increasing the use of their own internal platforms, meant that "you can start to influence the market at relatively low prices".
The news comes on the same day that Credit Suisse announced that it had fired from its stock trading department this week a trader who had caused a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The Bank immediately informed the competent authorities and is cooperating with their supervisory authorities.
"We believe that the trader acted alone and that the problem has been resolved", said Credit Suisse.
