Egypt inaugurates its first freely elected president
Muhammad Morsi has taken the oath of office, but his triumphant day will only bring political unrest to Egypt.
ISLAMIST Muhammad Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was inaugurated as the country's first freely elected president since Husni Mubarak was deposed 16 months earlier.
In taking office before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before 18 judges dressed in black talers in a mansion built overlooking the Nile that resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic", Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
"The Egyptian people today have laid the foundation of a new life - absolute freedom, true democracy and stability", said Morsi, a 60-year-old US-educated engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of fierce attacks by governments for most of its 84 years as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived shortly after 11:00 local time in a small convoy of cars, hundreds of soldiers and police were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of Mubarak's era, traffic was only briefly stopped to allow the convoy to pass through the usually busy road linking the city center to the suburbs to the south.
The personal prestige of Morsi, derisively dubbed the uncharismatic "spare tire" of the Muslim Brotherhood, has risen sharply since his victory and his Friday speech, which was intended to present him as the candidate not only of Islamists but also of all those who want to end the rebellion against authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state today", Mursi, dressed in a blue civil suit with a red tie, told the judges in the wood-lined chamber where he took the oath.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to deliver his inaugural address.
While standing by, he was given an official welcome by the military band, which played the national anthem.
The military commander, Field Marshal Husain Tantawi, was brought in.
His arrival was accompanied by the cheers of the army and the people, one hand out of the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the main lecture hall of the university.
Cairo University was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later became a bastion of the Islamic student movement in the 1970s.
Morsi took the symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year, and solemnly promised to resume the presidential powers taken from him by the military council, which took them from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take an oath of office before the court, rather than before Parliament, as is customary, he has submitted to the will of the army, suggesting that the struggle for power will continue.
Morsi's speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
