He travels through mud, river and jungle and provides free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural areas of Cameroon.
Bwelle and his team treat hundreds of patients almost every weekend
In West Africa, there are not many doctors; only one for every 5,000 people.
Vote here or on your mobile phone.
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 candidates for the 2013 CNN Heroes Award.
In the 2013 CNN Heroes Awards, you can vote for him or for any of the other top ten nominees.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father fall unconscious again and again and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near the Cameroonian capital Yaoundeo in 1981.
Initially, he was treated for a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that would plague him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon", says Georges Bwelle.
We'd have to take him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, where he received the kind of treatment that was simply available.
"It's not easy", says Bwelle.
You can leave your house at five in the morning, rush to the hospital to be the first one there, but you're not the first one.
There are many patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
Since 2002, when Bwelle's father died, things haven't changed much.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for every 413 people.
And even if doctors could visit Cameroonians, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the health care spending in this country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty", says Bwelle.
They can't enjoy life because of their poverty.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his countrymen suffering, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé General Hospital.
And he started a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, whose members go to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others crammed into trucks, strapped medical supplies to roofs, and travel through rough terrain to villages in need of help.
They're not always accompanied by luck.
On more than one occasion, the vehicles have to push through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as true heroes: feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodations the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a cause for celebration, and Bwelle , with her wide smile and unbridled energy , is very willing to join in the local fun.
The next day, the team starts treating hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on each expedition", says Bwelle.
They come to the village from within a 60-kilometer radius, and they walk.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide a variety of medical care.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches or donated glasses or a free birth certificate - a document that schools require but that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgeries are usually done in a school building, at the town hall, or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery site to make room for another patient.
With the help of light from a generator, an operating room, and sanitary equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work into the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but the village musicians usually help the team to keep the motivation going.
"To keep us awake and to keep us working, they play the drums all night long", says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of their work.
The group  composed of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students  performed 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their help can mean a lot to the local population.
One man said that after her hernia surgery, he would be able to work again.
"It'll change the future of our family", the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private health clinics around Yaounde.
He says that this second job finances about 60% of his non-profit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
"I'm not sure when she actually sleeps", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers for the Bwelle group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who have come from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it's a great practice that they wouldn't get at home.
"Dr. Bwellem, we washed his hands thoroughly and removed bloodstains or held his instruments", O'Malley says.
You'll never experience that as a second-year medical student in America.
Student volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaoundé, Bwelle provides them with food, transportation and education.
"He is a hero, no doubt", says O'Malley.
This organization is giving its life and its desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
Bwelle's constant sweating is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job", Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh, easing their pain-- that's why I do it.
